The recent refurbishment to L4 of the LKS library has been redundant and disadvantageous to students. 

Library spaces are already scarce when it comes to examination periods, and replacing regularly shaped tables with circular spaces, sofas with low tables unfit for studying, and reducing the number of seats overall is frankly quite absurd from a student's perspective. 

A few detailed pointers should be made:
1. The study carrels in the quiet area were an efficient use of space, and provided students with quiet places to study in solitude. Removing them is a big mistake. 
2. The old computer tables that used to be right in front of the main lift lobby were a good place to study with plenty of seats. Now the number of tables have been reduced to less than half of its original capacity, and with even lesser seats. How do you justify this decision?
3. The new sofas at the lift lobby and the old quiet area do make the place cosier somewhat but you should only consider these kind of comforts when the main issue facing students have been resolved - i.e. the lack of seats. Removing already scarce seats just to beautify the place is quite ridiculous, not to mention these seats have low or NO tables at all which makes them impossible to study in. 
4. there are these new bar top style tables installed at the very end of L4 facing the campus green. They have sockets but the sockets don't work, so its rarely used by anyone. Not sure if any planning has gone into this but its a serious waste of space right now. 
5. I suppose the library has tried to compensate for the loss in seats by now putting 6 chairs to a wooden table at the side of the library facing the campus green, where there were previously only 4 chairs to a table. This however is not exactly a very feasible solution. I would suggest that the library staff try to work for a day in those seats, 6 to a table rubbing shoulders while trying to work on a laptop and paper. If its not comfortable enough for them, it will not be comfortable enough for students who need to work on laptops/textbooks and papers. This means students will not want to share the seats beside them with others, which defeats the whole purpose of putting 6 seats to a table. 
6. At the start of this term the library rolled out a new printing system, which then malfunctioned and didn't work for over a week. They also removed the old printing system and hardware which meant students were left stranded without printing systems THROUGHOUT ALL SCHOOLS. This reflects some serious deficiencies in planning and testing the system even before launching it on the first day of school, and caused some great inconvenience to everyone. Right now it seems that the school has just gone straight back to the old hardware and system, so I'm not sure whether the significant sums that went into installing and purchasing the new system have been justified. 

Overall I would like the library to release an email to the school population detailing exactly how many seats have been removed from L4 LKS, what are the underlying reasons for such a change, and why have these changes not been properly planned (tables with no working sockets etc). Furthermore, the plan behind the new printing systems and its subsequent failure at the start of the term should also be explained to students so that they can be kept in the loop. Changes are usually welcome to a school thats been always wanting to take a step further, but changes that are inconsistent with students' needs are frankly quite ridiculous in an institution which was created to educate and serve students. I hope we at least can get some clarity and explanation for all these failures.

I have three points to make.

1. Loan of books on 3-hour course reserves is extremely tied-down by bureaucratic red-tapes. I had to borrow two books for one week's readings (of the same course) to make photocopies of particular chapters from each book. Yet I was only allowed to loan one book at a time. Which means i needed 6 hours (3 hours each book) just to get access to my compulsory course readings for one week! I explained my situation to the librarian at the counter, but he/she (to protect his/her identity) told me that the library's policy could not allow me to loan both books together... despite his/her understanding of my situation...

2. Printing service - constantly problematic (more a problem with IITS?) such as papers being stuck (yet no refunds!!), printers being down...

3. Students should be discouraged from placing their mobile phones on the study tables. Whenever their phones vibrate (so vibration-mode should also be discouraged if the phones MUST be on the study tables), it is highly distracting to other students. Imagine this: on a long table of 10 students sharing (such as at tables infront of windows), 3 or 4 students have their mobile phones on the tables - and given how frequent students receive messages on their telegram chats - the vibrations of the phones are almost unending... This is especially because how the study table is one connected piece of material, and the vibration is amplified (sound travels faster and louder via solid materials)... It is extremely distracting for other students wishing to concentrate.

I've been visiting LKS Library from year 1 to year 3, as I really enjoy having a quiet corner where I can focus on doing my work. To be frank, I'm more of a user who makes use of the spaces in the library, as compared to the wide resources available. I'm guessing that it's due to the lack of knowledge as to how to make use of the resources, apart from the occasional browsing of recommended textbooks. 

I would like to raise a concern of how the carpet is actually getting really dusty, which may be the cause of this light stench of smell which I've observed, getting from bad to worse over the years. I appreciate that there are cleaners who who vacuum and clean up the place every day, but maybe a more thorough clean up would be great for the well-being of all students and staffs. 
Another point I would like to note is how the drainage system at the toilets are quite bad, as I've seen urinals overflowing which is absolutely disgusting and may pose as a safety hazard to the users, since the floor in the toilets are all wet. This is especially so for the male toilet on level 4. I understand that the volume of users (especially during exam period) is super high, which may be the cause of the not-so-pleasant experience, but I believe more can be done for all of us to enjoy the LKC library - since we spend at least 10 hours a day during study week in the building. 

For project work in the project rooms, I understand that there's a Via app where we can connect our laptops to the projector wireless, but it is quite limited and laggy at times, and we do miss having the convenience of merely plugging in a HDMI cable. The library has invested so much in new LCD TVs, and it'll be a waste if we're not fully maximising the use of the HD screens, as the wireless capability is still not as stable compared to a wired connection. It'll be great if we can still have those cables made available in the rooms, to save us the trouble of heading back down to the counters to borrow one. 

In terms of the artistic setting, I really enjoyed the works which were put up by the photography club a few semesters ago, along the staircase from level 2 to level 5. There are actually quite a lot of spaces for such exhibits, to showcase the works of students. These artefacts actually beautifies the library, and I actually look forward to visiting the library when such works are displayed. Also, I would also like to commend the team behind festivals such as halloween, as well as the marketing team behind the Instagram and SnapChat accounts - those are things that are fresh, and not replicated by other libraries. Well done SMU Library!

Library Staff should take a tour around the libraries of other universities and Polytechnics and see where these other libraries have done well and how they do it. 

For example, Ngee Ann Poly has only one library but they serve the needs of over 10,000 students. In their designated discussion/non-quiet corners at level 1, they allow students to discuss over food and drinks. In the designated quiet corners of the library at level 4/5, they enforce no noise rules very strictly by patrolling staff. They don't depend on individuals to keep out the noise via ear plugs, unlike SMU's libraries. Additionally, SMU is stopping the giving out of free ear plugs.
